    id: "chaitra-and-akhara",
    pageType: "content",
    title: "Chaitra Parva and the Akhara",
    body: "Chaitra Parva takes place in the month of Chaitra, usually around April. It has long given Chhau an important public setting in and around Baripada. Accounts describe organised performances where groups, musicians, and audiences meet during a season of observance and artistic preparation. The celebration has changed over time. No single account describes it forever. [2][3][6]\n\nThe akhara is central to this work. The word refers both to a training ground and to the people organised around it. Students repeat foundational exercises, movement phrases, entrances, and repertoire under senior guidance. Musicians do not arrive as an extra on performance night. Dancers and musicians learn each other’s cues during practice. [2][4][6]\n\nAn akhara supports several kinds of memory at once:\n\n- bodily memory, held in repeated exercises\n- musical memory, held in patterns and cues\n- social memory, held in relationships between senior and junior members\n- repertory memory, held in inherited pieces\n- local memory, held in stories about earlier teachers and performances\n\nEach akhara has its own way of teaching. Gurus and groups differ in terminology, emphasis, repertoire, and correction. The categories in this eBook help readers compare evidence. They are not laws.\n\n> Listen: When a rights-cleared Mayurbhanj recording is added, listen beyond the dancer’s steps. Find the cue which prepares the action, then the accent which completes it.\n\n> 3D sandbox: The planned Mayurbhanj akhara study should separate training, music, and festival views. Follow one path from the practice area to the performance entrance, then locate the musicians. Publication waits for a named Mayurbhanj practitioner and musician to confirm the layout, references, permissions, and credits.\n\nThe festival gives training a public destination. The akhara provides the dancers and musicians who sustain it.",
