    id: "same-story-different-dance",
    pageType: "content",
    title: "The Same Story Does Not Become the Same Dance",
    body: "The same confrontation will not become the same dance in all three Chhau styles.\n\nA Mayurbhanj treatment might use unmasked group design, wide travel, and a broad range of movement through space. The face stays visible, while kinetic phrasing and rhythm carry the dramatic structure. [4][5]\n\nA Seraikella treatment might concentrate attention through a smaller masked figure, carefully placed head and body angles, and a solo or duet design. Published repertoire includes Ratri, Ardhanarishvara, Mayura, Krishna, Nabik, Banabiddha, and Hamsa. Each version still needs lineage-specific reference. [9]\n\nA Purulia treatment might enlarge the confrontation through vivid masks, costume scale, Jhumur narration, and forceful group action. Mahisasur Mardini is a well-documented example. Even troupes presenting the same subject use different masks, costumes, and performance choices. [8]\n\nThese differences are not a ranking:\n\n- Seraikella is not better because a movement is small.\n- Purulia is not less refined because a movement is large.\n- Mayurbhanj is not more expressive because the face is visible.\n\nEach form answers questions of visibility, character, and rhythm in its own way.\n\n> 3D sandbox: Compare entry, silhouette, use of space, mask-body relationship, musical layer, and final pose. Do not ask, “Which one tells the story best?”\n\n> Think: Which detail did each style ask you to watch most closely?\n\nA 3D figure shows contour, angle, and pathway. It does not reproduce live drums, the surrounding audience, the dancer’s breath, or the teacher’s influence on the phrase.",
